The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business
 Thursday, May 13, 2004 				 Coca-Cola paints rural Bengal red
 A STAFF REPORTER				 	 Coke vice-president Sunil Gupta in Calcutta on Wednesday. A Telegraph picture																								Calcutta, May 12: Coca-Cola India has deepened its rural penetration in Bengal by bringing into its fold more than 5,000 villages and increasing the number of distributors to more than 700.																								This is part of the companys strategy to tap the huge rural population. The company is already present in 1,70,000 villages in the country and plans to add 40,000 more by the year-end.																								The results have been encouraging with the company registering a turnover of $900 million in the financial year 2003, a growth of 22 per cent over the previous fiscal, vice-president, public affairs and communication, Sunil Gupta said.																								The total market for beverages in the country is estimated at Rs 19,000 crore and that of carbonated soft drinks Rs 7,000 crore, which is growing at around 22 per cent, he added. 																								Bengal holds a strategic position in the companys operations. Coca-Cola India has already invested Rs 8 crore in this year and over Rs 46 crore in the past two years.																								The company also plans to extend its country-wide retail network by 24 per cent in the current financial year, thus taking the count to 1.24 million. 																								At present, in rural Bengal, more than 85,000 outlets sell Coca-Cola products. The companys countrywide consumer base stood at 240 million in 2003 and it plans to increase it to 300 million in 2004. 
